	<td>
	  <font size="2" face="Verdana">
		Subject:&nbsp;<b>RE: Aggro Management</b></font>
		
		<a href="MB_Editmsg.asp?FID=68&FN=Ranger&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=1988838&TN=Aggro+Management&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=1989177&PL=4&amp;action=REPLY"><img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/btn_reply.gif" border="0" align="right" alt="Reply to message"></a>
		<br>
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/Icons/icon1.gif" border="0" align="ABSCENTER" width="15" height="15">
		<font size="2" face="Verdana">
		<font size="1" face="Verdana">posted 7/3/2003 5:58:18 AM&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=68&FN=Ranger&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=1988838&TN=Aggro+Management&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=1989177&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">Aggro management means the ability to gain AND lose aggro at will Nosferatu, not just gain, and in that sense, Rangers 51+ in level have the best set of tools for doing both jobs.</P><P>I can at will take (barring low HP frenzy) and give back aggro.  Other hybrids, like Paladins and Shadowknights, are great at gaining aggro quickly, but don't have the tools to give it back nearly instantly.</P><P>For the original poster, if you are lower than 50th level, you will need to rely on proximity to the NPC you are fighting (prox aggro), your weapon selections, and your casting to aggro management.</P><P>In terms of Prox Aggro, all NPCs have some form of a prox aggro.  For some, its the most important, for others its less so... ie Undead are almost purely prox aggro, and will attack whichever melee is closest to them.  To manipulate prox aggro, if you don't want to be the one to be hit, stand at the maximum range from the NPC that you can still hit it with melee, and make sure the tank is standing as close as possible.  If you want to maintain aggro, get as close as you can.</P><P>(Note:  You can force any mob into using prox aggro if you can root it.  Any rooted mob always hits the closest person on its aggro list, unless that mob can summon)</P><P>In terms of weapon selections, if you want to keep aggro, use fast 1H weapons, or extremely high ratio 2H weapons, and weapons with procs if you can, especially weapons that proc a stun or a debuff.  Just as NPCs react with different amounts of aggro to certain spells, they react with different amounts of aggro to certain procs... ie Ykesha (DD + Stun), Slow (Debuff), etc are all old high aggro weapon procs.  If you don't want to take aggro, then you will need to pick your weapons based on what the tank has, or only melee in spurts... attack a few rounds, turn off attack for second, then attack for a few rounds.</P><P>In terms of spells, until 51st level, the only spell you really have that will help you dump aggro is Root, and thats only because it forces prox aggro.  At the same time, Root is the only spell you have that will bypass low HP frenzy as well, for the same reason.  Other spells that extremely effective at obtaining and maintaing aggro though are Tangleing Weeds/Snare/Ensnare/Entrap and Flamelick/Immolate.  Flamelick and Snare though will probably be your bread and butter spells, especially Flamelick, which is a double action spell that both gives the NPC a DOT (3 HP/tick), but also lowers its AC (debuff).  Its also extremely fast casting, and few mobs will take more than 1 before turning on you.</P><P><BR>Fletcher<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
</tr>
