		<hr size="1">"In fact, ALL of the rangers I encounter don't want agro."</P><P>There is a difference between wanting aggro, and being able to tank.  I would prefer not being the one getting beat on by the NPC if there is another player in the group that can handle the job.  It frees me to do other things, like CC or damage (archery or melee)or pulling.</P><P><BR>"Being able to tank in Some zones and being able to hold agro doesn't make me a tank.... "</P><P>In the case of rangers it does.  They just need to be aware of their limitations, but a ranger tank is a better option than sitting LFG.  They may not always be the best option, but thats the definition of "situational".  Especially when you are talking about the typical experience areas for the 58th level druid that Gorse was addressing.</P><P><BR>"Why the hell would I want a ranger to hold agro for me when i don't care about the hits, lol."</P><P>You probably meant that as a rhetorical question, but the answer is that 1) the Ranger should have more HP than  you (base 60th modifier is 4.2 for rangers, 3 for shaman iirc), 2) higher AC due to skill caps making your mana use lower, 3) higher DS to speed up the fights (at 65th I can self buff to 62 DS), and 4) it frees you to deal with adds  or stack dotswithout worry about interuptions.</P><P><BR>"I don't want a Ranger holding agro for me the planes either because that palnes mob is going to chew through that rnager and come after me next."</P><P>With the kinds of slows a shaman is capable of putting onto a mob, Enchanters can tank in Teir 1 zones.  The benefit of having a hybrid tank is that the shaman can slow on incoming (or actually pull with slow) and the tank will still peel the mob before it ever hits the shaman.  Considerably less mana use for healing if the mob is slowed like that compared to the slower needing to wait a few seconds to let aggro build.<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
