		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=68&FN=Ranger&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=1988838&TN=Aggro+Management&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=2009674&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">"but if a warrior has a better tuaght that does not mean the knight classes are, how did you put it, aboslutely 0 use in a group. that is total BS and you should feel ashamed to make such a horrid statement. the higher xp and raid game is all about DPS. both knight classes have way better DPS then the warrior class. that is why they have lower HP/AC then a warrior. same thing with monk, and rogue, both classes have extrordinary DPS, but extreemly low HP/AC. its a fair trade off.... blah blah blah"</P><P><BR>There is not a single, valid line in that entire post Rick.  Thats amazing.</P><P>1) Knights and Warriors compete for the same position in experience groups... tanking the mob.  No group, with the plethora of monks, wizards, mages, rogues, rangers, and necros picks up a knight or warrior for DPS.  If Warriors were given the ability to hold taunt better than a knight, and maintain their superior HP and AC, Knights would be rejected from groups spots instantly, except for those sympathy groups that can't find an LFG Warrior, or a group of friends filling a spot.  Look at what Kurnak did to the knights for a lesson.  But don't take my word for it... go visit The Paladins of Norath site and propose to them it would be ok if Warriors had better taunt, because knights still had higher DPS.  I'd love to see that post.</P><P>2) Knights only outdamage warriors if their gear is vastly superior, the warrior is using Defensive, or the its a situational encounter, like Undead, or the SK has HT ready.  But fact is, a warrior with offensive oriented AAs and a good weapon (BOW or better) puts out about 140-150+ DPS, and matches or slightly exceeds my ranger's melee DPS with a similiar weapon.</P><P>3) At the raid level, DPS is only half the equation, and indirectly proportional to the importance of HP/mana management.  The higher your DPS, the lower your HP/Mana management can be, the lower your DPS, the higher your HP/Mana management has to be.  A raid 50 rogues with their best weapons won't do you a bit of good against Blazzax, and a raid of 50 clerics will fail just as miserably against him.</P><P>4) HP/AC is not the counter-point to DPS that is used to balance classes.  It is a factor, sometimes more important, sometimes less, depending on what class you are comparing (rangers to warriors for example), but in the case of the classes considered tanks (knights and warriors) the counterpoint at this stage to AC/HP is ability to hold aggro and mitigate/avoid damage.</P><P>5) I said giving warriors a method of aggro, particullarly snap aggro, that was superior to knights would make knights an extremely marginalized class.  They would have 0 role in experience groups, barring some situations where you had no means of CC and needed an offtank, but even then, another warrior would be better.  Well, SKs could fall back on pulling I suppose, but given bards are hands down the best puller now, followed by monks, then enchanters, its a fairly crowded pool of classes to fill that slot as well.</P><P>6)  In the 50+ game, the ability to tank is weighed against the ability of the healers to manage their mana.  If a group has the mana regen to maintain a relatively constant level with either a warrior or a ranger as the tank, then despite the lower HP/AC of the ranger, he will make the better tank due purely to aggro management.  But thats the majority of the current issue with Knights and Warriors. While most groups don't have the mana regen to support the average ranger as a tank, and the very high end rangers that can tank with the average group aren't common, its typical for any group to have the ability to support any knight in an experience group at the same mana cost as a warrior.  That makes knights vastly superior tanks with their aggro generating abilities, unless Defensive is required.</P><P>7) Saying any knight or warrior will always be a better tank than any ranger is dangerous.  It would be far too easy to use examples of those classes with disparate levels of equipment to prove you wrong.  It wouldn't be typical though, but certianly not an "always" condition.</P><P><img src='http://www.everlore.com/gimages/shades.gif' width=15 height=15 align=middle> In the 30s and 40s there is 0 difference between the Defensive of  Warrior and that of a Ranger, as there is no difference in their Offense and Weapons skills.  On top of that, the Sta to HP modifier that dictates the average HP levels of those classes is extremely close.  You would see very little difference if any in the exp rate of a 35th level group with a Ranger or a Warrior as MT.  The real shift doesn't occur until 50+, but those with no real experience that read too much what others say like to move that level range down and assume it applies at lower levels.</P><P>9) Rangers are hardly number 2 in melee DPS rankings.  An equally well equip'd monk easily outdamages me in pure melee, and since my melee and my archery DPS are nearly identical, outdamages my normal archery DPS as well.  Its only when using TS I equal or exceed the DPS of a rogue.</P><P>10) You might play a high level warrior, but that doesn't mean its high end.  And judging by your posts to this forum and the Warriors section, you are hardly an end game player.  But then, I was of the impression we played on the same server, so if you want to post your warriors name, prove me wrong.</P><P><BR>Fletcher<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
