		<hr size="1">Well, there are a few factors that put bards there, and some of the are restricted to the high levels.</P><P>1) As good as Harmony of Nature is for splitting a single mob out from a crowd, its restricted to outdoor use only, lasts just 42 seconds and is limited to 65th or under level mobs.  Bards have a song with nearly the same abilities, but isn't restricted to outdoor use, giving them the flexibility of using where we can't.</P><P>2) High level bards with lots of AAs (my apologies here... my only real experience is with guild bards, or bards from other guilds at relatively the same level, and they all have 150+ AA, so my veiwpoint is skewed a bit) have an Ability called Fade.  Its basically Memblur on steriods, and completelly wipes a bard from any aggro list.  Combine this with the ability to Snare or Mez a mob, and a bard can single pull a mob to just about anywhere as long as they have mana (Fade takes a large chunk of mana, and the only things that increase a bards mana regen rate are Mental Clarity AA points and FT items.... no songs or spells work on them).</P><P>3) The ability to pull with a debuff, which is also what makes Shaman and Enchanters great pullers as well.  Once the bard has their target singled, they can finish the pull with debuffs, so that by the time the mob gets to the camp, its already slowed, etc.  A knight takes over aggro and the group kills.</P><P><BR>Of course, none of this addresses the actual abilities of the person playing the character.  I'm just considering the tools available to the classes that give a higher level of safety.  however, a magician that understands pathing, social aggro, aggro range, etc will make a far better puller than a twit bard who only knows to play Chorus of Marr.</P><P>Fletcher<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
